annotations:
You came to hurt me in all the right places
 Made me somebody

Pain tends to fuel songwriting, and Indigo De Souza has multiple songs about heartbreak and pain (Real Pain, The Sun Is Bad, What Are We Gonna Do Now, etc). The songs she wrote about getting hurt helped her to be discovered by more people, making her “somebody” and increasing commercial success.
It’s just ’cause I get so tired of filling the space all around me
sometimes entertaining ourselves can get exhausting and we just need somebody to take over for us to distract us from whatever else is going on in our heads :)

They’re constantly comparing themself to those around them and wondering why they can’t seem to function the same as everyone else seems to, a common experience of many depressed people.

annotations: When am I gonna find a better man
The speaker knows they’re not happy in this relationship but they don’t know where to find someone better for them so out of fear of being alone they just stay.
I don’t love you, I like you

This line further cements the speaker as different from everybody else, because usually people are nervous to tell someone they don’t like just them but love them. Here, it is reversed and the singer subverts our expectations. I always accidentally sing this line backwards because it is such the opposite of our expectations.
Like everybody else does, everybody else does?
In this song, the singer compares themselves to her peers and achievements they seem to accomplish.

annotations:
What are we gonna do now?
 What are we gonna do, baby?

The speaker is hinting that something is going on between their partner and them.
They’re wondering where they will go from here – will they mend their relationship or end it?

I’ll be the one
 I’ll be the one to deliver the news
The speaker will be the one to end the relationship since their partner believes this is how relationships work and will not do it themselves.

When are we gonna wake up
 In some cubicle cell with our shirts tucked?

This lyric suggests that they feel that their life will fall into the same monotony as their relationship. Their relationship no longer feels exciting, so when will their life go the same way with them becoming just a 9-5 cubicle worker?
I’m so loud in the mornings
It sounds as if the singer views themselves as a nuisance, most likely because their partner complains about them.
Saw you sleeping in bed with your day clothes on
Seems like they’re overworked/overtired constantly- giving up on the peace and tranquility stability can provide

I know you’re worn, you’re exhausted
 This is love, this is lost on you
 I’m holding my night
 In your hands
 And there’s nothing like trying
The speaker has a lot of emotional dependence on their partner and is trying to make things work between them but their partner is exhausted and isn’t putting in effort

When are we gonna wake up
 In some cubicle cell with our shirts tucked?
 I’ll be the one
 I’ll be the one to deliver the news
Basically, the speaker is saying that they aren’t going to call it quits in their relationship until they both go crazy, and when it happens, the speaker is going to be the one to leave.

Just this once won’t ya?
 Hold me closer
 Tell me I’m all that you need!
The person feels unloved by their partner and wants their partner to show that they love them

Sleeping outside with a red nose
 Sleeping in bed with our day clothes on
There isn’t a lot of love left in the relationship, and they’re just going through the motions of life with nothing happening. Kind of like zombies.

And I’m never cooking up what you’re craving
 I’m never cooking up what you’re craving
This person can’t provide what their partner wants, and they feel inadequate for it

body.plain: Here, the speaker knows that their relationship is unhealthy and the other person makes them feel inadequate, but they stay because they want to believe that at their core, their partner is good and deserving of love.

annotations: I want to believe that you’ve got a good heart

The repetition of this line could indicate that the narrator is trying to believe that their love interest is a good person, even though they have evidence to prove otherwise. The love interest has caused the narrator to feel self-doubt and self-blame.
I’m nothing but trouble, baby believe in me

The singer’s partner has made her doubt herself to the point she believes she is the problem. She wants to believe that there is good in her partner so the easiest conclusion is to believe that she must be doing something to cause her partner to treat her this way.

I’m not the girl you thought I was
 But I am close, close enough
 Was it something that I said
 Is it the way I stood so still and never moved

The unhealthy relationship is making the singer feel as if they are not good enough. She is beginning to second guess all of her words and actions because her partner is critical of everything she does.

annotations:
Ah, come when you’re called
 If this is all we’ve got to work with then it’s all we’ve got to blame
 Ah, come when you’re called
 If this is all we’ve got to work with then it’s all we’ve got to say
 I’m lovin’ your skin darlin’, I’m lovin’ this hard morning
 I need to be kicked, maybe fucked, maybe told I’m in the way

The relationship dynamic is harmful, but it continues anyway. The narrator wants to be mistreated and objectified because it feels familiar and reliable (“come when you’re called”). The narrator encourages others to mistreat her and might get herself killed if it continues.

Did you say anything on the night of my first hit
 On the night of my first kiss
 On the night of my first runaway

I think the “you” in that song is probably more of a “me”. A lot of the time, even though I write lyrics as if they’re directed towards someone, I think they are really more directed toward the old and new embodiments of myself.

– Indigo De Souza, The Grey Estates
